➜China to provide COVID-19 vaccines to developing countries: Singaporean newspaper
http://www.sohu.com/a/437259006_162758	37061
<p><img src="http://p7.itc.cn/q_70/images03/20201209/780f2fcbeef744b19720909b73cdb1c8.jpeg" /></p>
<p>Screenshot shows the news report published by Lianhe Zaobao on Dec. 5, 2020.</p>
<p>Chinese President Xi Jinping’s special envoy Wang Yi, also Chinese state councilor and foreign minister, said China will provide COVID-19 vaccines to developing countries during a virtual speech at the United Nations (UN) General Assembly special session in response to COVID-19 pandemic on Dec. 3, 2020, Singapore’s Chinese-language newspaper Lianhe Zaobao reported.</p>
<p>Wang noted in his speech that China is accelerating phase III clinical trials of COVID-19 vaccines. Once completed and available for use, they will be provided to developing countries as global public goods.</p>
<p>In an interview with Lianhe Zaobao, Li Mingjiang, an associate professor at S. Rajaratnam School of International Studies (RSIS), Nanyang Technological University, Singapore, said that Chinese President Xi Jinping and other officials had repeatedly noted on several occasions that China-developed COVID-19 vaccines will be provided to other developing countries on a priority basis. It is a clear plan of China awaiting for implementation.</p>
<p>Wang Yizhi, a professor at School of International Studies of Renmin University of China also said in his interview with Lianhe Zaobao that China’s plans to provide COVID-19 vaccines were already presented before. Wang Yi’s virtual speech at the UN General Assembly made the plans more explicit.</p>
<p>Find the original article at https://www.zaobao.com/special/report/politic/cnpol/story20201205-1106275</p>
